vlaanderen.be/departement-zorg/nieuwsberichten/3-kinderen-in-lier-besmet-me=
t-varkenslintworm-geen-reden-tot-ongerustheid</a>=0D<br>=0D<br>=0D<br>In mi=
d-June [2023], 3 children from the same primary school in Lier<br>were diag=
nosed with pork tapeworm infection. The Healthcare Department<br>is still i=
nvestigating the source of infection, but the risk of more<br>infections is=
 extremely small. The school, parents, and the primary<br>care zone of Lier=
 were informed and supported.=0D<br>=0D<br>The pork tapeworm is very rare a=
nd [is not thought to - Mod.LL] occur<br>in Belgium or Europe. The source i=
s most likely contaminated food of<br>foreign origin. The investigation int=
o the source of the contamination<br>is ongoing. During the summer holidays=
, the Care Department started a<br>stool test among about 50 teachers and t=
heir family members and<br>several people involved in preparing food at sch=
ool. The results of<br>this study are expected during this month [I was not=
 able to find such<br>results - Mod.LL]. In addition, the Department of Car=
e is also<br>launching a survey among parents about possible travel to area=
s where<br>pork tapeworm occurs and their dietary patterns.=0D<br>=0D<br>Jo=
ris Moonens, spokesperson for the Department of Care: "We currently<br>have=
 no hypothesis as to where the children could have become<br>infected. Pork=
 tapeworm does not occur here, and the only link we see<br>between the chil=
dren is that they go to the same school. The<br>infections could also have =
happened years ago and are only now causing<br>symptoms. We must therefore =
take into account that we will not be able<br>to find out where the source =
of the contamination was. Nevertheless,<br>we estimate the chance of furthe=
r infections to be extremely small.<br>Pork tapeworm does not occur here, a=
nd the 3 infected children<br>themselves are and were not contagious."=0D<b=
r>=0D<br>We ask parents to be vigilant, especially in case of symptoms such=
 as<br>prolonged headaches, epilepsy, or vision problems. The general<br>pr=
actitioners and pediatricians in the area are aware. Two new<br>information=
 sessions are planned at the school next week. The<br>Department of Care an=
d the school work very closely and well<br>together.=0D<br>=0D<br>--=0D<br>=
Communicated by:=0D<br>ProMED<br><br>[Lier is located in Antwerp province i=
n northern Belgium.=0D<br>=0D<br>ProMED was not aware of this report when t=
he incident was first<br>reported and would like more up-to-date informatio=
n about the cases<br>and the cluster follow-up. The specific manifestations=
 of _Taenia<br>solium_ infestation in the schoolchildren is not stated, but=
 the<br>symptoms mentioned in the last paragraph suggests that the disease =
was<br>neurocysticercosis. Cysticercosis is due to infestation with the<br>=
intermediate (larval) form of the trematode and is acquired, not by<br>inge=
sting food containing the larval form, but rather ingestion of<br>food or w=
ater containing _Taenia_ eggs. The latter would occur if a<br>food preparer=
 who was harboring the adult pork tapeworm contaminated<br>the food with th=
e microscopic eggs. Neurocysticercosis generally<br>occurs in adults (the a=
ges of the children were not stated but they<br>were primary school student=
s).=0D<br>=0D<br>Cysticercosis, therefore, is not an infestation acquired b=
y eating<br>tainted pork. An example of a larger outbreak of neurocysticerc=
osis,<br>which occurred in Orthodox Jews who did not eat pork, is shown her=
e:=0D<br>=0D<br>Schantz PM, Moore AC, Mu=F1oz JL, et al. Neurocysticercosis=
 in an<br>Orthodox Jewish community in New York City. N Engl J Med. 1992; 3=
27:<br>692-695; doi: 10.1056/NEJM199209033271004.=0D<br>-------------------=
---------------------------------------------------------------------------=0D=
<br>"Abstract=0D<br>-------=0D<br>Background and methods: From June 1990 th=
rough July 1991,<br>intracerebral infection with the larval stage of the po=
rk tapeworm<br>_Taenia solium_ was diagnosed in 4 unrelated persons in an O=
rthodox<br>Jewish community in New York City. None of the patients had eate=
n<br>pork, and only one had traveled to a country in which _T. solium_<br>i=
nfection was endemic. We investigated this outbreak, screened serum<br>samp=
les from family members and household contacts for antibodies to<br>cystice=
rcosis, and examined stool specimens from household employees<br>for eggs o=
f _Taenia_ species.=0D<br>=0D<br>Results: The 4 patients had recurrent seiz=
ures and brain lesions that<br>were radiologically consistent with the pres=
ence of cysticerci. The<br>diagnosis was confirmed in 2 patients by a brain=
 biopsy, and in 2 by<br>immunoblot assays for cysticercus antibodies. Of 17=
 immediate family<br>members screened serologically, 7 from 2 families had =
cysticercus<br>antibodies. Magnetic resonance imaging of the brain showed c=
ystic<br>lesions in 2 of the seropositive family members, one of whom had h=
ad a<br>seizure. Examinations of 6 domestic employees from all 4 households=
<br>revealed an active infection with _Taenia_ species in one and a<br>posi=
tive serologic test in another. Since these women had recently<br>emigrated=
 from Latin American countries where _T. solium_ infection is<br>endemic, t=
hey were the most likely sources of infection in the members<br>of these ho=
useholds.=0D<br>=0D<br>Conclusions: A diagnosis of neurocysticercosis shoul=
d be considered in<br>patients with seizures and radiologic evidence of cys=
tic brain<br>lesions, even in those who do not eat pork and who have not tr=
aveled<br>to a country in which _T. solium_ infection is endemic. Recent<br=
>emigrants from countries in which _T. solium_ infection is endemic<br>shou=
ld be screened for tapeworm infection in their stools before they<br>are em=
ployed as housekeepers or food handlers."=0D<br>=0D<br>A follow-up serostud=
y of this population, which I helped run, found a<br>significant seropositi=
ve rate in the community:=0D<br>=0D<br>Moore AC, Lutwick LI, Schantz PM, et=
 al. Seroprevalence of<br>cysticercosis in an Orthodox Jewish community. Am=
 J Trop Med Hyg.<br>1995; 53(5): 439-442; <a href=3D"https://u19268662.ct.s=
endgrid.net/ss/c/TUIVIg4PCmni5tP3Q8lzBceVuvEuhD1iiZCc1-Kus-C-Xve1Bdqg_xRlKw=
